217. Contains Duplicate — from a beginner’s mindset
https://leetcode.com/problems/contains-duplicate/
What might seem like an easy question for a person with solid leetcode experience, might seem like an absolute nightmare for a beginner.
Let’s break it down
Approach 1
The question asks us to return true in case an element exists at least twice else return false. So let us think. How can we do this? One might think that for an element that exists in nums, we could find for an instance of that element in the rest of the array. Thus we should get
class Solution {
public:
    bool containsDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++)
        {
            for(int j = 0; j < nums.size(); j++)
            {
                if(nums[i] == nums[j]  && i != j)
                {
                    return true;
                }
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
};
Perhaps we have a solution that satisfies the test cases. Lets submit it.

Oh? What just happened? Lets have a deeper look. The time complexity that we have here is O(n²). This seems to be ineffective for larger inputs.
Approach 2
Perhaps, one would think it is unnecessary to scan through the previous element. I mean, if we did have a pair that satisfies the answer, it would have returned true already. So why should we check the previous elements altogether? It also improves our time complexity to O(nlogn).
class Solution {
public:
    bool containsDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
        for(int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++)
        {
            for(int j = i + 1; j < nums.size(); j++)
            {
                if(nums[i] == nums[j])
                {
                    return true;
                }
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
};
It satisfies the test cases again. Hopefully, we have the solution now. Lets submit again.

Ugh! Not again. So they just want O(n), is it? Lets think harder.
Approach 3
We need to check for the same element twice so how about we keep a data structure that stores every read element and we could search for the element for element of the nums array. But do we have a data structure with quick look up for elements? Couldn’t be an array for sure. Lets try a set. Seems appropriate right? We can search up the element and push it in as and when needed and the lookup is quick too. Lets code it out.
class Solution {
public:
    bool containsDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
        set<int> check;
        for(auto& num : nums)
        {
            if(check.count(num))
            {
                return true;
            }
            check.insert(num);
        }
        return false;
    }
};
It runs the test cases properly but would it submit successfully?

Finally, we have a solution. But can we optimise it further? The beats 5% runtime and 10% memory does not seem comforting at all. Why did this happen though? Although sets may make your code to look like it runs in O(n), the insertion and search of a set, by itself, takes O(logn). Perhaps, the illusion of success has taken to the best of us.
Approach 4
God this has taken fairly long now. But let us try getting it even more better. Lets see what we can do. If sets aren’t efficient, we certainly need O(1) lookup in some other data structure. Maybe we can make a frequency map of every element that exists in nums. Hmm, to do so, we need to access key-value pairs. Lets try a hash table. Lets set the hash map and insert elements as per their frequencies in nums.
class Solution {
public:
    bool containsDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
        unordered_map<int, int> hash;
        for(auto& num : nums)
        {
            hash[num]++;
            if(hash[num] > 1)
            {
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
};
Runs the test cases again. Lets submit.

Finally, some success.
Approach 5
What if I don’t want to use any data structure altogether but I still want an efficient output. Hmm, lets see if we could do that. After all, these integers are values. How about we sort them? We’d get the same value integers consequently in the array in that case. We might get a time complexity of O(nlogn) but the space complexity would be unparalleled with.
class Solution {
public:
    bool containsDuplicate(vector<int>& nums) {
        sort(nums.begin(),nums.end());
        for(int i = 1; i < nums.size(); i++)
        {
            if(nums[i-1] == nums[i])
            {
                return true;
            }
        }
        return false;     
    }
};
Lets submit.

Perhaps we have the perfect balance between space and time complexity.
